HEADWORD: Infeudation
<hw>In`feu*da"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>infeudatio</ets>, fr. <ets>infeudare</ets> to enfeoff: cf. F.
<ets>inf⟦eacute⟧odation</ets>. See <er>Feud</er> a fief.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The act of putting one in
possession of an estate in fee.</def> <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The granting of tithes to laymen.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infibulation</ent>⟦br⟧
